18)
map() --> transforms each element of a stream into exactly one new element.

flatMap() flattens the nested structure.
It takes each element (in this case, each List<String>), turns it into a Stream, and then merges all those streams into one continuous stream.

| Feature        | `map()`                                         | `flatMap()`                             |
| -------------- | ----------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| Transforms     | One element → One element                       | One element → Many elements (flattened) |
| Resulting type | Stream of the same shape (may be nested)        | Stream flattened to one level           |
| Example here   | `Stream<List<String>> → Stream<Stream<String>>` | `Stream<List<String>> → Stream<String>` |
| Use case       | Change each element                             | Flatten nested structures               |


🧠 Quick analogy
Think of map() vs flatMap() like a box of boxes:
map() opens each box, performs something, then puts the box back — you still have boxes inside boxes.
flatMap() opens all the boxes and pours everything into one big box.

